<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <%- include('../partials/head'); %>
  <style>
    .jumbotron {
      padding-left: auto;
      padding-right: auto;
      padding-top: 5em;
      max-width: 1024px;
      margin-left: auto;
      margin-right: auto;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: 2.5em;
      font-weight: bold;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
    }
    h2 {
      font-size: 1.8em;
      font-weight: bold;
      margin-top: 20px;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    h3 {
      font-size: 1.5em;
      font-weight: bold;
      margin-top: 20px;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    ul {
      list-style-type: disc;
      padding-left: 20px;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
    }
    li {
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    p {
      margin-bottom: 15px;
    }
    .grid.has-2-cols {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      gap: 1rem;
    }
    .cell.box {
      height: 100%;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      padding: 1.25rem;
    }
    .cell.box h3 {
      margin-top: 0;
    }
    .cell.box p, .cell.box ul {
      flex-grow: 1;
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
  <%- include('../partials/header'); %>
</header>

<script>
  document.getElementById('tsunamis-nav-item').classList.add('is-active');
</script>

<main>
  <div class="jumbotron">
    <h1>Tsunamis</h1>
    <p>Tsunamis are powerful series of ocean waves that can cause devastating damage to coastal areas. Understanding the warning signs and knowing how to respond can be crucial for survival.</p>

    <div class="columns pt-3">
      <div class="column p-3">
        <img src="images/NOAA-alaska-tsunami.jpg" alt="Tsunami Aftermath of 1964 Alaska Tsunami" width="99%" style="border-radius: 12px; filter: drop-shadow(2px 6px 8px #000000bb)">
        <p class="pt-3" style="color: #cccccc; text-align: center; font-style: italic">
          Alaska 1964 Good Friday earthquake and tsunami damage.<br/> Photo by NOAA.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="column p-3 pl-5 ml-2">
        <h2>What to do during a Tsunami</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Get to high ground immediately - aim for at least 100 feet above sea level</li>
          <li>Stay away from the beach and coastal areas</li>
          <li>Wait for official "all-clear" before returning - tsunamis can come in series of waves</li>
          <li>If you can't reach high ground, go to the upper floors of sturdy buildings</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="columns pt-2">
      <div class="column p-3 fixed-grid">
        <h2>Key Facts</h2>
        <div class="grid has-2-cols">
          <div class="cell box is-flex is-flex-direction-column">
            <h3>Warning Signs</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Sudden receding of ocean water</li>
              <li>Approximately 5 minutes warning time after water recedes</li>
              <li>Loud roaring sound like a train or jet</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cell box is-flex is-flex-direction-column">
            <h3>Did you know?</h3>
            <p>About 80% of tsunamis happen within the Pacific Ocean's "Ring of Fire," where tectonic shifts make volcanoes and earthquakes common.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cell box is-flex is-flex-direction-column">
            <h3>Speed & Power</h3>
            <p>Tsunamis can race across the sea at up to 500 miles (805 kilometers) per hour, crossing the entire Pacific Ocean in less than a day!</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cell box is-flex is-flex-direction-column">
            <h3>Warning System</h3>
            <p>The Pacific Tsunami Warning System, a coalition of 26 nations, maintains seismic equipment and water level gauges to identify tsunamis at sea.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="columns pt-3">
      <div class="column p-3">
        <h2>Causes of Tsunamis</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Undersea earthquakes at tectonic plate boundaries</li>
          <li>Underwater landslides</li>
          <li>Volcanic eruptions</li>
          <li>Large meteorite impacts in the ocean</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="column p-3">
        <h2>Characteristics</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Usually composed of multiple waves (wave train)</li>
          <li>Can appear as massive breaking waves or quickly surging tides</li>
          <li>Wave height may be only a foot in deep ocean but grow tremendously near shore</li>
          <li>The wave trough often reaches shore first, causing a vacuum effect</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="jumbotron" id="sources" aria-label="Sources">
    <ol>
      <li><a id="source-1" href="https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/article/tsunamis">Tsunamis Facts and Information</a></li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</main>

